### 1. Brief Summary of the Facts  
The case involves *HKSAR v. Chan Ming Lok* [2009] HKCFI 571, where the appellant, Chan Ming Lok, was convicted of possessing an offensive weapon under section 33(1) of the *Public Order Ordinance* (Cap. 245). The facts centered on Chan being stopped by police in Central, Hong Kong, at 1:45 a.m. on 29 June 2008. Police observed him acting suspiciously—walking slowly, repeatedly looking around, and adjusting his rucksack—leading to his detention. A small domestic knife was found in his rucksack. Chan claimed he carried the knife for self-defense while returning to Shenzhen (where public order was allegedly poor), as he worked as a chef and traveled late at night alone. He admitted the knife was used for self-defense but denied intending to cause injury in Hong Kong. The magistrate convicted him, finding the knife an "offensive weapon" under section 2 of the Ordinance and rejecting his self-defense claim as lacking "imminent danger." Chan appealed, arguing the magistrate erred in classifying the knife as an offensive weapon under the now-questionable "suitable for causing injury" category (category (c)), and sought a reduced sentence. The appeal succeeded on sentence (reduced from 6 to 4 months) but failed on conviction.  

